Rating: 2
My boyfriend asked me to make cabbage soup. I'd never heard of it, but I found this recipe. I carefully read the reviews and decided to practically double the mace, with which I have no experience, and ruined the recipe. We couldn't eat it. The mace overwhelmed it. I love nutmeg, but not mace, at least not in this quantity. Oh well. It's all about learning, plus just another way to make my boyfriend doubt that I truly did attend culinary school. He has strong doubts about why I'm still paying the student loans, and so do I.

Rating: 3
Made this soup (twice) for my cooking club and everyone loved it. The first time, I followed the recipe except substituting nutmeg for mace--very good. The second time, I took the advice of some of the other cooks, and increased the chicken broth/milk ratio (2:1 instead of 1:1). I also used mace (doubled the quantity) and it went from very good to excellent--I barely had to add any salt and pepper for taste. Both times I used savoy cabbage, for color and flavor.

Rating: 3
I also made this last night as the starter for our Saint Patty's meal. Agree it is a very nice soup, the cabbage is so mild this way it wouldn't offend anyone (so mild my 15 year old spiced it up with a bit of hot sauce). But with lots of fresh chives (that are just beginning to return to my herb bed) it was great. Will try the addition of kale next time for a variation.

Rating: 3
Made this for St. Patrick's Day last night. It was very nice and creamy, but the cabbage flavor was not very strong, hence a little bland. Next time I might add some green onions or a little kale, more salt and maybe a little more mace.

